# Tailwind Rules

## Utility-first conventions
- Prefer Tailwind utilities over custom CSS for common styling.
- Keep class names grouped by purpose: layout -> spacing -> typography -> colors -> effects.
- Avoid inline style unless the value is truly dynamic and cannot be expressed with Tailwind tokens.

## Responsive design
- Build mobile-first by default.
- Use breakpoints consistently: `sm`, `md`, `lg`, `xl`, `2xl`.
- Do not duplicate entire class groups across breakpoints unless necessary.

## Design consistency
- Use project spacing scale (`p-`, `m-`, `gap-`) consistently.
- Reuse color and typography tokens from `tailwind.config`.
- Prefer semantic component patterns for repeated UI blocks (button/card/badge variants).

## Readability and maintainability
- Keep class strings readable; extract repeated patterns using reusable components.
- If a class list exceeds readability, use helper composition (`clsx`, `cva`, utility builder).
- Avoid conflicting utilities (example: multiple `text-*` or `bg-*` in the same state scope).

## State and interaction
- Always define clear hover/focus/active/disabled states for interactive elements.
- Use `focus-visible` styles for accessibility.
- Keep transition usage intentional; avoid over-animating basic interactions.

## Dark mode
- Support dark mode using `dark:` variants where relevant.
- Ensure contrast is accessible in both light and dark themes.
- Test key screens in both themes before merging.

## Performance and build hygiene
- Avoid dynamic class name construction that prevents Tailwind purge from detecting classes.
- Prefer safelist only when dynamic classes are unavoidable.
- Remove dead classes and stale utility patterns during refactors.

## Collaboration checklist
- New UI must be responsive at minimum on mobile + desktop.
- Reused style patterns should be centralized into shared components.
- Visual changes should include before/after screenshots in PR when possible.
